A new course at Harvard University this year allows all its pre-graduate students to sleep more in an effort to counteract the growing macho culture of study by working out caffeine driven 'all-night sessions'.
An academic found that students at the world's top university are often ignorant when it concerns the basic principles of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believed was the first of his kind in the U.S.
He was inspired to start the course after he gave a talk about the effect of sleep withdrawal on learning.
'At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why do they tell me first, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had told her how important sleep was--that surprised me,' he told The Telegraph.
The course, presented for the first time this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their general well - being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves some interactive tasks.
In one department there is a picture of a dormitory, where students on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books must click to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another department, participants are told how long-term sleep reduction can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
'We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know--just as you have the right to know the health effect of choosing to smoke cigarettes,' said Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride to 'study all night' still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and ever increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
To make sure that you get enough sleep of good quality, a student's 'secret weapon' should be to avoid stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said--even to avoid putting on weight, because sleep withdrawal puts the brain in a starving mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californiar who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course after having walked one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to work for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete.
Prof. Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of 'blue light' that electronic screens and LED lights radiate, which may disturb your circadian rhythm and may cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
